            <dd>1962.68</dd>

            
                            <dt>Title</dt>
                <dd>Cheek Piece for Bridle Depicting a Horse</dd>
            
                                                                                                                                                                                                  <dt>Other Titles</dt>
                    <dd>
                                                                                                                                      Alternate Title: horse bit (cheek piece)                                                                        </dd>
                            
                            <dt>Classification</dt>
                <dd>Riding Equipment</dd>
                                        <dt>Work Type</dt>
                <dd>
                                                            cheekpiece                                                      </dd>
                                        <dt>Date</dt>
                <dd>10th-mid 8th century BCE</dd>
                                        <dt>Places</dt>
                <dd>
                                                            Creation Place: Ancient & Byzantine World, Asia, Luristan (Iran)                                                      </dd>
                                        <dt>Period</dt>
                <dd>Iron Age</dd>
                                        <dt>Culture</dt>
                <dd>Iranian</dd>
                            <dt>Persistent Link</dt>
                <dd><a href="https://hvrd.art/o/289239">https://hvrd.art/o/289239</a></dd>
          </dl>
        </dd>

        
                <dt>Physical Descriptions</dt>
        <dd>
          <dl>
                          <dt>Medium</dt>
              <dd>Bronze</dd>
            
           
                        <dt>Technique</dt>
             <dd>Cast, lost-wax process</dd>
           
                          <dt>Dimensions</dt>
              <dd>8.6 x 12.7 cm (3 3/8 x 5 in.)</dd>
            
                          <dt>Technical Details</dt>
              <dd>
                                                      <p class="divider">Chemical Composition: ICP-MS/AAA data from sample, Bronze:<br />
Cu, 90.68; Sn, 8.33; Pb, 0.16; Zn, 0.001; Fe, 0.06; Ni, 0.26; Ag, 0.02; Sb, 0.06; As, 0.41; Bi, less than 0.025; Co, 0.021; Au, less than 0.01; Cd, less than 0.001<br />
J. Riederer</p>
                                      <p class="divider">Chemical Composition: EMP analysis from sample, Bronze:<br />
Cu, 91.28; Sn, 6.26; Pb, 0.06; Zn, 0.00; Fe, 0.05; Ni, 0.26; Ag, 0.01; Sb, 0.02; As, 0.25<br />
 <br />
 <br />
T. Richardson, June 1999</p>
                                      <p class="divider">Technical Observations: The patina is dark green, and the object is a solid lost-wax cast. It has a rounded head and raised prongs on the reverse that were formed with the original model. The tail, loops, collar, and raised area on the bit were added to the original wax model, as opposed to being formed in a mold. However, it is possible that the main shape of the horse was modeled in a one-sided mold by pressing or pouring in wax. Then the raised prongs and other features were added to the model, and the model was cast. Therefore, the cheek piece may have been produced using a combination of the indirect and direct lost-wax methods. There are prominent casting flaws on the object.<br />
 <br />
 <br />
Tracy Richardson (submitted 1999)</p>
                                                </dd>
            
            
            
            
            
          </dl>
        </dd>
        
